# Source Commenting Standard

Code in `src/` must be understandable without reading implementation details line-by-line.

- Add comments for non-obvious intent, trade-offs, invariants, and sequencing.
- Prefer short "why" comments over "what this line does" comments.
- Add a brief comment before multi-step logic, state transitions, or retry/backoff flows.
- Document assumptions and failure behavior at integration boundaries (Redis, SQLite, IMAP, webhooks).
- Keep comments current; update or remove stale comments in the same change.

## Required Cases

- Queue ordering, idempotency, or stale-reconciliation behavior.
- Escalation/confirmation gate logic.
- Any branch where incorrect behavior could dispatch the wrong outbound action.

## Avoid

- Obvious narration comments.
- Large comment blocks that duplicate type names or function names.
